<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 11 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information Vol. 17, No. 24 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec2>

Taura syndrome in the United States of America
--------------------------------------
(Date of previous outbreak of Taura syndrome in the United States of
America reported to the OIE: 2000).
Emergency report
Information received on 10 Jun 2004 from Dr Peter Fernandez,
Associate Administrator, Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service,
United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), Washington, DC:
Date of the report: 10 Jun 2004.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 30 May 2004.
Estimated date of primary infection: 25 May 2004.
Outbreaks:
Location No. of outbreaks State of Texas, Cameron County (in the
central southern part of the country) 1 farm
Description of affected population: _Penaeus (Litopenaeus) vannamei_
(Pacific white shrimp).
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
cru / 2 000 000 / 3 ponds / 90 percent / 0 / 0
Diagnosis: farm managers noticed increased bird predation at 2 ponds
and found shrimp in the ponds to be weak and dying. Water quality was
tested prior to submitting samples for diagnostic testing.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Texas Veterinary Medical
Diagnostic Laboratories (TVMDL), College Station, Texas. Samples are
being submitted to the OIE Reference Laboratory at the University of
Arizona.
B. Diagnostic tests used:
- histology;
- in situ hybridisation;
- polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
Control measures: facility is under quarantine and harvest for human
consumption will be allowed
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Among the references below are a couple of excellent comments from
Paul Epstein highlighting the role of environmental factors and
immune system modulators in the development of Taura syndrome. -
